  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Immunosuppression is the leading cause of death in septic patients. Neutrophils are classical
      components of innate immunology, but recent studies showed that neutrophils might display
      antigen presenting function and inhibit lymphocyte proliferation by expressing programmed
      cell death 1 ligand 1 (PD-L1). Whether neutrophils express PD-L1 and its role in
      immunosuppression during sepsis remain unclear.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
